Hong Kong Stocks Advance as Cnooc Earnings Beat Estimates

-- B y   J o n a t h a n   B u r g o s
-- 
2011-03-24T03:43:33Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-24/hong-kong-stocks-advance-as-cnooc-earnings-beat-estimates.html
Hong Kong  stocks advanced, sending
the benchmark Hang Seng Index to its highest level in almost two
weeks, after  Cnooc Ltd. (883)  posted earnings that exceeded analyst
estimates and raw material suppliers gained.  Cnooc,  China ’s biggest offshore oil producer, climbed 2
percent after saying 2010 profit increased 85 percent to a
record, beating estimates. Jiangxi Copper Co., China’s No. 1
producer of the metal, and  Aluminum Corp of China Ltd. (2600) , the
nation’s largest supplier of the metal, gained more than 2
percent after a gauge of industrial metals in London rose to a
three-week high yesterday.  “Earnings have generally been quite good,” said Terrace Chum, the Hong Kong-based managing director of greater China
equities for Manulife Asset Management, which oversees $210
billion. “I’m slightly more positive. Besides rising oil prices
and geopolitical risks, my biggest concern is China, whether the
government will overdo policy tightening.”  The  Hang Seng Index (HSI)  gained 0.8 percent to 22,996.08 as of
11:41 a.m. in Hong Kong, heading for its highest close since
March 14. Seven shares advanced for every two that declined
among the index’s 45 companies. The gauge slumped 4.1 percent
last week, the biggest weekly drop since February, amid concern
 Japan ’s strongest earthquake and damage to a nuclear plant would
cripple the world’s third-biggest economy.  The Hang Seng China Enterprises Index of H shares of
Chinese companies increased 1 percent to 12,883.78. Futures on
the Hang Seng Index climbed 0.9 percent.  Copper, Gold  Cnooc advanced 2 percent to HK$18.80. The company said
yesterday annual net income increased 85 percent to 54.4 billion
yuan ($8.3 billion), a record high, from the previous year. That
compares with the average estimate of 52.4 billion yuan by 18
analysts in a Bloomberg survey. PetroChina  Raw material producers gained after the  London  Metal
Exchange Index of prices for six industrial metals including
copper and aluminum jumped 2.3 percent yesterday to a three-week
high.  Jiangxi Copper rose 1.5 percent to HK$24.20. Aluminum Corp.
of China gained 2.2 percent to HK$7.40.  Zijin Mining Group Co., China’s biggest gold producer,
increased 1 percent to HK$6.05. Zhaojin Mining Industry Co., a
gold miner, added 2.1 percent to HK$34.80. Immediate-delivery
bullion gained as much as 0.5 percent to $1,441.16 an ounce
today, near its record $1,444.95 set on March 7. It was trading
at $1,437.65 as of 10:45 a.m. Hong Kong time.  Shares of China’s biggest lenders advanced on expectations
they will report record profits for at least the fourth year as
credit demand bolstered by economic growth fueled an average 29
percent growth in earnings.  Banks Advance  Industrial & Commercial Bank of China (1398)  Ltd., the nation’s
biggest lender by market value, rose 1.1 percent to HK$6.21.
China Construction Bank Corp., the second-largest, gained 1.3
percent to HK$7.19. Bank of China Ltd., which is scheduled to
announce full-year results today, increased 0.7 percent to
HK$4.16.  The Hang Seng Index Volatility Index, the benchmark gauge
for Hong Kong stock options, fell 1.9 percent to 18.98,
indicating that options traders are expecting a swing of 5.4
percent in the next 30 days.  To contact the reporter on this story:
